To handle null arrays, you can add a null check at the beginning of the method. If either of the arrays is null, you can return false. To handle cases when the arrays are different, you can keep track of a boolean variable and set it to false if there is any mismatch in the values at corresponding indices. Then, return the boolean variable after the loop.

    public static boolean areIdentical(int[] data, int[] table) {
        if (data == null || table == null) {
            return false;
        }

        if (data.length != table.length) {
            return false;
        }

        boolean identical = true;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; data.length; i++) {
            if (data[i] != table[i]) {
                identical = false;
                break;
            }
        }

        return identical;
    }

You cannot return when elements are equal, or you will always return `true` if the first elements are equal.

Then you need to check for `null` explicitly, if you want to allow `null` values.

You can simplify the `if (!(a == b))` to `if (a != b)`. You should always use curly braces in `if` and `else`, it makes the code easier to read and when you later add more statements, you need them anyway.
Finally, if you already return in the `if` for the array length check, you don&#39;t need an `else` when the arrays have the same length.

```java
public static boolean areIdentical (int[] data, int[] table) {
    if (data == null &amp;&amp; table == null) {
        return true;
    }
    if (data == null || table == null) {
        return false;
    }
    if (data.length != table.length) {
        return false;
    }
    
    int pos = 0;
    while (pos &lt; data.length) {
        if (data[pos] != table[pos]) {
            return false;
        }
        pos++;
    }
    return true;
}
```

